The big comeback of the Czech loser is approaching.
Pavel Francouz called up to the NHL
Czech ice hockey goaltender Pavel Francouz, who is going through a difficult period in his career, is returning to the NHL.
The 31-year-old Pilsen native will be on the bench and could soon be in goal.
The former goalkeeper of Litvínov, Plzeň and Russian Chelyabinsk was injured during the NHL preparation in October this year.
He was swapped in the middle of the game with Vegas and since then he has not appeared on the NHL ice.
The incident happened as the experienced goalkeeper moved from one post to the other.
"Pavel Francouz will be out approximately three to four weeks with a lower-body injury," the team announced in early October.
His return to the NHL net eventually stretched to more than two months.
He was called up from the farm on Sunday morning American time, where he had caught four games and showed his old form.
In the AHL, he recorded 94.5% of saves.
The Pilsen-born hockey player wants to finally make it and prove that he belongs in the best league in the world.
He had hip problems in his last season and didn't play a single game in the shortened pandemic season.
In the NHL, "Francík" played 36 games, his save percentage is 92.3%.
