A story of returning to one's roots that turns out to be just a wistful illusion.
The bohemist and comparatist transfers the fairy tale of Little Red Riding Hood to the setting of a contemporary village.
Her delivery of the brutality surpasses the folk versions and escalates into a horror of emotional emptiness.
And that the path back to instincts is shorter than one is willing to admit
The author's penultimate novel tells a less sentimental story about returning from emigration than we are used to hearing.
Those who stayed and those who left know too little about each other to make a go of it.
Trains start running according to the new timetable, some operators will change
From Sunday, trains will run according to a new timetable.
The biggest change is the replacement of transport providers on some routes, such as between Ústí nad Labem and Kolín, where instead of Czech Railways, RegioJet will start running.
For most lines, only the departure time will be changed, and in some cases, the route will be slightly changed.
There will also be dozens of new trains on the tracks.
The transport companies started selling tickets already in the autumn.
České dráhy plan to run an average of 6783 passenger services per day in the new timetable, of which an average of 478 will be long-distance trains.
Trains will travel approximately 118 million kilometres during the new timetable.
In addition to domestic connections, the new timetable will also include routes to Germany, Poland, Slovakia, Hungary, Austria and Switzerland.
The company will introduce dozens of new trains along with the new timetable.
The main novelty will be the InterJet trains, which will run on the Prague-Cheb line.
The transport company will send other new trains to northern Moravia or western Bohemia.
The transport company will also traditionally increase the price of tickets next year, by an average of 3.2 percent.
The railways take inflation into account in their tariffs every year.
The biggest change in the RegioJet timetable is the entry into service on the R23 line Ústí nad Labem – Mělník – Nymburk – Kolín.
The transport company will replace České dráhy here after winning the Ministry of Transport's competition.
RegioJet will operate a total of 16 trains on the route every day, eight in each direction.
Other changes concern long-distance connections between Prague and Brno, which will also stop at Havlíčkův Brod, Žďár nad Sázavou and Kolín from Sunday.
Leo Express retained its 16 connections, two return connections to Slovakia and also weekend connections to Krakow.
According to spokesperson Emil Sedlařík, the transport company also tried to keep the timetables of its long-distance trains as similar as possible despite the planned works.
The operation of Arriva trains and other carriers should continue without major changes.
The transport operator will also change on some regional lines.
Changes are expected for passengers in the Českolipsko region, where instead of Czech Railways, trains from the German company Die Länderbahn will run on the line from Mladá Boleslav via Česká Lípa to Rumburk.
Passengers will also be able to use a unified ticket on the railways in the second year.
Like Czech Railways, their price will increase by the inflation rate of 3.2 percent.
I have to disagree.
Don't we learn to see the other side's point of view?
Everywhere we hear how much they had to fight for their rights, how they were oppressed and had to work hard and die.
In my life, I have never heard a teaching from the perspective of the slave-owning side or from that time. No one is defending this, only condemning it.
No one tells you in school that black people often sold other black people into slavery and that they were often the worst slave owners.
No one will teach you at school that the colonisers often bought the land from the Indians, all they will tell you is how brutally we, the Europeans, exterminated them, when in fact they had been killing each other for a long time.
I also spent some time in the USA, directly at schools, both in the north and in the south.
I have not come across anyone deliberately covering up facts, but I have heard before that it happens and I think it is a problem, I do not deny it (for example, in Japan, the atrocities of WW2 are quite taboo).
My point was more that history is not black and white and that we have a tendency to look at it from today's perspective without understanding.
History doesn't care about people's feelings, it just is what it is and I think it's a fatal mistake to condemn it without looking at it in the context of the time.
On the other hand, we should learn from it and never repeat it.
By the way, while we're on the subject of the southern states, yes, the Confederate flag and famous slave owners are quite popular there, on the other hand, they also had some good achievements and it seemed absurd to me to reject them.
Moreover, the North was not much better, as many people idealise it today.
And a lot of people forget that not everyone in the South was a slave owner and a lot of things were repugnant to them.
I wouldn't compare this with the Russians, they intentionally omit some facts, lie and manipulate, moreover, our point of view doesn't exist there (there was a video on YouTube from a television station where they cut off someone who started talking about our legionnaires and 1968).
What I found ridiculous about US schools was the rise of Marxism and the idealization of communism, something their country has never experienced.
Overall, I found that at some universities it was terrible, those students were quite radicalised and the schools often supported them in that.
And when I think of these people being much older one day, it makes me a bit sick that this could be the voice of the majority, because it is among the young and even in the ruling elite.
I feel like feminism has already achieved what it was supposed to and it's no longer about the same thing, it's become radicalized.
