TV has fallen out of love with Christmas films, with 200 premiering this year
Los Angeles - Cinemas, television channels and streaming platforms in the United States and other English-speaking countries have given in to the trend of Christmas films and this year will present a record number of more than two hundred premieres to their viewers.
The operator of the film database IMDb counted them.
The genre of Christmas family and romantic films has been scoring with the audience in recent years and has significantly increased viewership, so more and more of these films are being made.
This year, four times as many Christmas movies were made as in 2011 and twice as many as five years ago.
The IMDb database only includes those films that have the word Christmas in their title, so there are actually many more Christmas films.
The movies that people traditionally associate with Christmas have always been there.
In the Czech Republic, this period is associated with fairy tales, and worldwide, films such as Home Alone, Love Actually or the classic Christmas story It's a Wonderful Life from 1946 are popular.
The real boom in Christmas films, however, started in 2009, when the American cable television channel Hallmark came up with a special film series, recalled the BBC website.
Her Christmas project called Countdown to Christmas then included four films and was very successful.
This year, the station began to tune its viewers into Christmas on October 22 and will present a total of 42 Christmas films.
Competitor network Lifetime has 35 new Christmas-themed movies on its schedule this year, and popular streaming services like Netflix are also contributing to the total.
"In this magical time of year, the story doesn't matter so much, what's important is that there are a lot of Christmas trees in the background and that it's snowing," Brandon Gray, the author of a book on Christmas movies called I'll Be Home for Christmas Movies, said with a smile.
"For the audience, it's a form of escape and a way to feel a little bit of peace for at least two hours in the midst of all the holiday madness and the craziness of the world we've been living in for the last few years," Gray added.
He says that the Hallmark channel, for example, uses the same recipe for its films, which is uniform but successful.
You have two people who fall in love, but then there is a misunderstanding about half an hour before the end, which is successfully resolved and the two kiss.
It's the same thing over and over again, and as long as all the films look the same and have the same atmosphere, people watch one after the other, adds Gray.
