How the pandemic has affected intimate life: The number of people under 35 who are without sex for a whole year is growing
More and more young adults in the U.S. are living their lives without sex.
It is mainly religious people, says the DailyMail website.
The survey found that the proportion of people under 35 who abstain from sex has risen from eight to 21 per cent between 2008 and 2021.
Women aged 18 to 35 who say they have not had sex in the past year are at an all-time high.
Other factors are also contributing to the decline in the number of sexually active people, according to a survey by the Institute for Family Studies (IFS).
One of them could be the economic impact of the coronavirus pandemic and a higher unemployment rate.
However, the presence of the media, social networks or video games, which make sex less and less of a priority for young people, could also have played a part.
"Since 2010, there has been a rapid increase in the share of men and women aged 18-35 who report not having had sex in the past year," said IFS researcher Lyman Stone.
In married people, sexual activity is more common, with only 5% of them saying they had no sex in the last year in 2021.
For singles, it was 29 percent. Stone added that marriage under the age of 35 is only a small percentage.
The decline in sexual activity is also due to the fear of premarital sex and religious beliefs.
While married couples are more likely to be sexually active, the percentage of married and cohabiting women under 35 is still falling.
Young people are divided on premarital sex, with about 30% seeing it as a bad thing and about 70% seeing it as okay.
"It's true that they are a minority among single people in this age group, but their behavior is shifting the trend," Stone says of the 30 percent.
For most of those who have a moral problem with premarital sex, the reason is religious.
Among single people under 35 who attend religious services more than once a month, the rate of abstinence has increased from 20 per cent to almost 60 per cent since 2008.
Among the "less religious," the trend has risen from 10 to 20 percent," Stone said.
Other factors, such as less social interaction and especially social drinking of alcohol during the pandemic, also contribute to the decline in sexual activity.
The study also showed that the likelihood of sex is lower for people who are unemployed or have lower incomes.
Another reason could be the expansion of digital media, which apparently reduces the need for sex.
People are spending more time online, which is "substituting" for this need.
This trend has taken hold mainly during the lockdown period of the coronavirus pandemic.
The whole Covid vaccination mandate is about whether society should force a portion of the population to do something they don't want to do, but that could save their lives.
It's a pretty tough question, and the one I'm most interested in personally is the question of social conscience.
That is, for example, the question of whether if we don't tell them and they die, it will be our fault.
My argument is that we could certainly have been responsible for the death of an eighty-year-old man who didn't really know much, we didn't explain it well to him, he heard some misinformation, and as a result, he didn't get vaccinated and eventually caught it and died.
On the other hand, I don't think we can be blamed for the death of a stubborn vaccination opponent who rants here alongside the SPD and the KSČ about bullying and a totalitarian state.
From the statistics I mentioned, it is quite clear that the majority of unvaccinated pensioners probably belong to the second group, so they will be able to blame themselves for it.
