Skiers headed to the mountains over the weekend, where there was plenty of snow and good weather
The Czech mountain resorts experienced the first major influx of skiers this weekend.
After the heavy snowfall at the end of the working week, there is no shortage of snow and some ski resorts have opened.
The skiers were not deterred by the requirement to show a COVID certificate at the ski lifts.
While tow operators aren't complaining about a lack of customers, some ski equipment rental shops are reporting weaker demand for their services than before the pandemic.
Thousands of people took to the cross-country ski trails and ski slopes in the Liberec Region over the weekend.
The weather was kind to the skiers today, offering both sunshine and excellent snow conditions.
"We are satisfied, the opening weekend really started on Friday evening when we had the first skiers on the hill," praised the director of the Ještěd Sports Area, Jakub Hanuš.
Hundreds of people headed to the Jeseníky Mountains for the first weekend of skiing in the new season.
Ski Aréna Karlov and the centre in Branná in the Šumperk region were open.
Weekend attendance was very good, with an estimated 400 people on Saturday and today.
The conditions are great.
Today the sun was shining, it was around minus three degrees, so perfect, said Rostislav Procházka, the representative of the ski resort in Branná.
Ski resort operators can only sell lift tickets to people who are vaccinated or have recently recovered from COVID-19.
With the exception of a few people, people are prepared and show the necessary documents, said René Hroneš from the Špindlerův Mlýn ski centre to ČTK.
"We've only seen a handful of incidents," he added.
Some ski rental and equipment stores are reporting less demand than before the pandemic.
Fortunately, there is interest in renting skis.
It is not like in previous years, but there are still enough customers, said Alexandra Bokišová from the Opava Skiopava store.
They expect a greater influx of visitors during the ski courses.
The manager of the Hradec Králové company Snowbear, David Šinták, also feels that due to the coronavirus, there is not as much interest in renting ski equipment as there used to be.
By this time before the pandemic, we were already being loaned out.
Compared to the period before the pandemic, we are at about 50 percent, Šinták told ČTK.
According to him, people have become lazy during the pandemic and have learned to sit at home.
On the other hand, the rental shop in the Novako area of Boží Dar is experiencing high demand.
They started renting skis there a week ago and those interested have to order them in advance.
"We start renting skis this weekend, but people have already called in advance, so we expect a lot of interest, just like last year," said the facility's operator, Pavlína Nováková.
According to her, the interest is comparable to the period before the epidemic also in the ski school.
