Hungary is due to hold elections in the spring that could end Viktor Orban's 12-year rule.
They will be elections of European-wide significance.
How fair can we expect them to be?
They won't be fair.
They will probably not be free either, because the last two elections under Orbán were not free either.
His Fidesz party controls the media, changes electoral district boundaries to its advantage, and does other small or large tricks.
The most recent one sounds like everyone can choose where they want in practice.
This will allow Fidesz to transport voters from decided districts to those where the outcome is uncertain and the opposition could win.
So I'm just repeating that they won't be fair at all.
Do you think it will be as unfair as in 2014 and 2018?
After all, the situation is very different.
Before, it was not about whether Fidesz would win, but by how much and whether it would have a constitutional majority.
Now there is a real chance that the united opposition will win more votes and seats.
This is a big change for Viktor Orbán and his party.
Will they play even harder in an effort to hold on to power?
Yes, we have some indications that they are ready to go beyond what they have done so far.
Recently, a recording of the Speaker of Parliament and one of the leaders of Fidesz, László Kövér, was leaked to independent media, in which he explains to the heads of the secret services that the opposition is a threat to national security.
Are these the hints of a new approach you're talking about?
Yes, that is one of the new things.
It all starts with the tongue.
I was beaten quite often, the last time when I was 14, my mother doesn't have much patience, neither do I, my father has it for a long time, but then he hits me extremely (only in connection with me).
I am also very choleric and I used to get very angry when I was little, to the extent that I would lie on the ground in a fit of rage and turn blue, they would have to take me under the shower to calm me down.
Sometimes they would spank me as a form of discipline, sometimes it was more that they didn't know what else to do.
I definitely have a tendency to solve things with violence now too, I used to fight a lot when I was little, now I at least hit something to let off steam, and when I was younger I might have slapped my parents on the hand, for example (so that I didn't get hit too hard), so nothing extreme, but I always have this urge.
I'm not able to determine to what extent it is due to my explosive nature, but certainly the upbringing also has its part to play.
I'm afraid that I'll also lose patience with my kids and handle it the same way.
I think that hitting children is just wrong and that my parents shouldn't have done it, especially not at that moment when it was no longer "educational" but out of frustration. On the other hand, I think that every parent messes up at some point; it's probably not possible to not mess up your children at least a little, so I don't hold it against them.
