Another government ends and the law on the involvement of municipalities in the selection of a repository is nowhere
Minister Karel Havlíček's proposal needs a major overhaul
The government of Prime Minister Andrej Babiš is coming to an end and the law that was supposed to ensure the respect of the interests of municipalities and their citizens in the selection and approval of a deep geological repository for high-level radioactive waste still does not exist.
The government's legislative council suspended the discussion of the proposal, which the Ministry of Industry and Trade submitted to the government after years of delays.
However, its content is in serious conflict not only with the affected municipalities associated in the Platform against the Deep Repository, but also with the Union of Towns and Municipalities of the Czech Republic.
Municipalities expect a significant strengthening of their decision-making powers with regard to the repository, which has been promised to mayors since 2011, when the first work on this legislation began, and which is required by the Czech Atomic Act and the European Directive.
We expect the new government to revise the proposal in cooperation with the municipalities in accordance with its coalition agreement.
The draft law by Minister Karel Havlíček, which Platforma has at its disposal, is criticized by municipalities mainly for the following: The proposed level of involvement of municipalities and the public in the decision-making process for the selection of the site for the repository is insufficient and cannot ensure respect for the interests of municipalities and their citizens.
It can only be truly effective if the municipalities or the public can influence whether the process will continue in a given location.
This can be ensured by imposing an obligation on the Repository Administration to request the consent of the affected municipalities before initiating a specific procedure.
The proposed draft of the land-use plan almost completely ignores the involvement of the public and turns the citizens of the municipalities into mere extras in the permitting process.
The draft lacks a systematic setting of compensations for municipalities for the entire process of searching for and selecting a site for the repository, its permitting, and operation.
According to today's legal regulations, representatives of municipalities do not have many options to defend the interests of their citizens when looking for a place for a repository.
Only in some permitting procedures can they submit their comments or appeal, but the authority or minister who is interested in issuing the permit decides.
The potential lawsuit does not have a suspensive effect on the carrying out of survey or construction work.
The co-decision of local authorities, which the Platform is calling for, is a principle commonly used in many democratically advanced countries and certainly in those that have already made progress in allowing storage facilities, such as Sweden and Finland.
The preparation of the law is another failure of the state administration, which hires external law firms to prepare legislation.
In this case, it is a contract with the law firm HAVEL & PARTNERS s.r.o., which was concluded by SÚRAO and follows on from contracts with lawyer Jan Zemánek.
According to the contract register, the total sum for this work is almost 4 million crowns.
Antonín Seknička, deputy mayor of the village of Cejle from the Hrádek area and spokesperson for the Platform against the Deep Geological Repository, said: After the ministers of industry, who only postponed the alignment of the position of local authorities towards state authorities in the search for a deep geological repository for highly radioactive waste to their successors, we expect a more significant change from the new government.
We also offer a helping hand.
We would also like to thank the Association of Towns and Municipalities, which perceives the issue of insufficient rights of municipalities for such a fundamental construction in a similar way as the directly affected municipalities in selected locations.
The platform against the deep repository brings together 51 members (35 municipalities and towns and 16 associations) to promote a change in the state's approach to dealing with spent nuclear fuel and other radioactive waste, which will not be limited to the deep repository.
The platform also advocates that the decision on the selection of a site for potential storage should be subject to the prior consent of the affected municipalities.
John Goodman (69) was scared into losing weight: He lost 90 kg.
Although he had no need to change his lifestyle for many years, he was eventually scared by doctors.
They told him that if he didn't lose weight, he would die.
And it worked.
Goodman has lost 90 kilograms, which is half of his original weight of 180 kilograms, reports The Sun.
He showed off his new figure in Los Angeles at the premiere of the animated series The Freak Brothers.
The fat guy from the Roseanne sitcom is a completely different person!
John liked to joke that his friends and family had asked him to lose weight because his large body was causing furniture to break.
"I was putting everything in my mouth," the actor said in a 2018 interview with AARP.
This time I wanted to do it slowly.
Move, exercise.
I'm getting to an age where I can't afford to sit on the sidelines, Mr Goodman told ABC, whose transformation is remarkable.
It also depends on what kind of boss and in what context you want to use the word "boss".
If it's some kind of text on a platform that expects readers from the gaming environment, I wouldn't translate it at all.
If it was a formal text, for example a university text, I would probably look for a way to describe or explain the boss.
And there are different types of bosses.
For example, a game like Dark Souls has several bosses, right, and so a "boss" is something like a lord/ruler of a given level, and then there is the final boss...
Many games have hidden bosses (super bosses, hidden bosses) that are not necessary to beat in order to complete the game or level, but are often stronger than regular bosses.
Then there are games like Half-Life, where bosses exist, but the player doesn't directly fight them (Tentacle, Gargantua), and can they be called bosses at all?
And then there are the mini bosses.
It is not really possible to translate the word "boss" in a single word. Czech and other languages do not solve this issue (Catalan, for example, is interesting in this regard, as it translates "boss" as the final opponent).
It is a computer-controlled opponent that is significant to the story or the game in general, stronger than all previous ones and guarding the completion of a level or task.
